This doesn't seem fair or right -- where is the integrity, are there any ethics in business here?

Loyal customers should not be held victim to predatory pricing tactics.</text>

<text>I have visited Marlowe twice now and had a great experience both times! They've implemented new COVID protocols (temp check, questions at the door, etc.) and put in plastic partitions at the manicure stations, so I felt perfectly safe going in for both a mani and pedi. I first got the Marlowe Mani and had Aiden as my nail technician. He was really great! I'm really pleased with how my nails turned out (smooth, shiny with beautiful shaping and cuticle work!).

The interior of the salon is super chic and clean. The staff were all incredibly friendly and attentive. I didn't have to wait to get started upon arrival. I also really appreciate the ethical practices of this business. A living wage is SO essential, and the quality of the service matches the price in my opinion.

I got my first Marlowe Pedi today. It was divine! I had Thi as my technician. She was wonderful. She really took the time to attend to the little details. My feet were a mess before a went in since I'm a dancer: lots of dead skin and calluses. She was both gentle and thorough as she attended to the bottoms of my feet, cuticles and areas around the nails. My feet look and feel great now! She even put my flip flops back on my feet for me when it was time to check out so that I wouldn't accidentally mess up my toenails. So sweet! I'd highly recommend Marlowe if you're looking for some high quality pampering.<//text>< pics>

<text>Clean and beautiful looking nail salon. They keep it simple and clean here. It's comforting to see a package of clean tools being opened before you. One of my biggest fears is a fungal infection from going to a salon so I've painted my own nails for many years. My partner booked me a manicure here for a special occasion. I brought my own nail color here, which is ZOYA brand and they have the basecoat and topcoat to match. They have a lot of ZOYA and OPI from what I can remember.

The staff is very friendly, welcoming. The place doesn't smell crazy like most nail salons since this place doesn't do acrylic or other heavier chemical processes. They don't have too many stations so I was asked to sit at the waiting area while my nails dried, which was fine. I think the music playing can get a bit overwhelming because it's high energy, but that's just me, I'm a quiet introverted person.

They have drying drops at the very end, which I've never used before. I was told to wait at least 1 hour for my manicure to dry before doing anything more intensive with my hands.

The person who worked on my nails was pretty quiet, but did a good job. I think I am just not used to my cuticles being cleaned up and pushed back so that is always a sensitive process for me. I did notice they felt dry the days afterwards, and a pit peely, so moisturizing the following days was a must.

I think the only criticism isn't heavy, but I do think I could have done a better job at the actual nail painting portion. There was some pooling at the cuticles. I thought at least a brush with acetone could be used to clean up the cuticles for a clean line, but maybe it has something to do with using new tools every time, so that's ok. I understand the nail professional needs to get through each client efficiently so they don't have all day to paint perfectly.

Overall a good experience. :)<//text>< Pictures>

<Pictures>None</Pictures><Resp>None<//Resp><Text>Very disappointing experience. I have been looking for a nail salon like this in the East Bay for awhile and had high hopes for this new space. The salon is aesthetically beautiful and they did offer beverages when we arrived, but that is where the positives stop.

I had scheduled a mani/pedi combo for both me and my mother the day before we were flying out on our trip. I made the reservation the day prior IN person and initially, the receptionist seemed friendly/accommodating. She said she was able to get us in together for a manicure but our pedicures would be staggered, one after the other. I handed over my credit card and reserved our appointments.

We arrived to the appointment and told the receptionist that we were there for a mani/pedi. As we were picking out our colors she informs me that we are only booked for manicures, in an accusatory tone. I told her no, I most certainly booked both and we had had a discussion about how long the services would be with them staggered.

We are seated and the receptionist comes back over and says again that its not on the schedule and she isn't sure what happened, that it must have been booked on a different day, but they are fully booked and can only do our manicures. Meanwhile, she keeps going back to the front desk to speak to another woman with her back turned (the manager/owner) and relaying everything I am saying to her. This is only a few feet away, so I can hear everything. The owner/manager never once turned around to acknowledge me and never came over to apologize for their error. From what I could overhear, she had a very "oh well" attitude.

Our mani appt was at 2pm. Their best offer was to do a single pedicure at 6pm and acted as if they were bending over backwards for this to work. Mind you, there is only one other person in the salon, mid manicure when we had arrived. No - I have a baby and I can't wait around for four hours to get a pedicure, this was already an effort to get time away. I asked if I could just shorten my manicure and get a quick file/polish change on my toes. As a new mother herself (the owner was outside with her infant when we got there) this is something I would think would resonate with her.

I understand that mistakes happen. There are scheduling errors and they were fully booked on Saturday. I get that. However, I didn't appreciate being made to feel like this was my problem. There was no effort by the staff to apologize (genuinely), to make things right by owning their mistake and making a shortened appointment work or at least offer something for their shortcomings to say, "hey, we are sorry your experience wasn't as expected, we hope you give us another chance." As we were leaving the salon, the owner was outside fussing over the sandwich board sign and never once looked up and said anything.

I am stunned by how terrible their customer service was.

During our manicure, we also overheard the receptionist and owner again whispering back and forth in a negative/inappropriate way about one of staff members who was black. The tone in which we witnessed them speaking to her was awkward and condescending.

To add insult to injury, my manicure was worse than at most random salons I've been to. The paint job was uneven and the top coat didn't fully cover all of the color with obvious brush stroke outlines. The paint also started chipping within 24hrs and by day 3 the polish looked pretty battered.

A beautiful space doesn't equate to a classy experience. Such a shame. I most certainly will not be back.</Text><Rating>1</Rating>< user_name>

[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMNckU1T4KBdqu1yppn-p-_X0kJ-M7M4npALrbo=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOaEodEWh_H20Dka8VPdKSiHsgFEoMXm6YTe2PA=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>
< review>
Very underrated store that offers great products at a decent price.

I have never heard or seen this place and it seems like it has always been here.  Their exterior and store logo is so awful that I thought it was some dollar store replica.

I was surprised to find that there is a very good selection of lamps.  Ceiling fixtures, exterior lighting, desk lamps, you name it along with some random furnitures.

The pricing is reasonable compared to many other stores like the strange one off stores in downtown or Z-Gallerie, etc.  Price tags were clearly placed for each product and the employees seemed eager to help.

I think the store needs to be better maintained and can definitely be shown a lot nicer.  A lot of dead bulbs and dark / quiet for a lighting store.

If you are looking to remodel your house, this is a must stop.</review>

<Text>So here is  problem - they have a lot of stuff, they can deal with customer issues excellently, they have a lot of lamps of modern design - yet there is a huge quality disconnect they haven't been able to fix.

All of their lamps are from China and there is absolutely no quality control. - I will now be on my 4th bedside lamp of the same design. WHy? Because it is the only design that looks good from all of the stores we have seen.

Yet its a failure. Why? Because the danged lamp cannot be made to hang plumb and level off the wall. Each one of the previous 3 have had serious quality and manufacturing flaws that make these swing lamps  look like a drunken sailor lurching  down the gang plank-. THe  mounting plate is absolutely square plumb, and level. The level bubble  just touches both of the center lines in all positions.

I mount the lamp on the base plate and immediately find that  even if the base  plate is level  -  the lamp part that is supposed to mate with the base plate is off  level by a half bubble. THis is not fixable with a shim.

It is so disappointing to see the crap being imported. Yet try to find anything else these days. I spent more in going back and forth to the store than the lamp is worth.

So find another lamp you say - well we have been looking for this particular type for 2 months because it fits the decor and I would have spent 3 times as much if the damned things actually fit. The poor people at the store are not happy to see me , and they treat me really well, but i will continue to return lamps until i get one that actually is plumb and level. <userid>108383554046352528073< /userid>< username>
William<//username>
<time>1529950462963<//time>< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< review>
Best mechanics and very honest. I took my car in after hearing some creaking sounds. I'm actually on a road trip from Chicago and came to visit and just came here based on a recommendation from some locals. I was concerned because I need to drive 2000 miles back to the Midwest and I didn't want my car breaking down halfway.

First off the mechanics were very honest to tell me that I had a certain problem and even documented it in detail and email it to me as well as printed it off.

Second, they gave a list of prices which I thought were fair, but also gave great recommendations on what to do. When I asked if I could drive safely to Chicago to get it fixed there, they were honest with me and probably ok, but to check it out in different states just in case.

Third, they did not charge me for looking at my car even though they lifted it up, and drove it around. I've had experiences in the past where mechanics have charged me money just to look at my car and did nothing, or were trying to push services that i did not really need. I'm an out of town traveler that does not know the city, is desperate, and scared that my car is going to break down. Some mechanics would probably have taken advantage of me and charge me for services that I did not need. But these guys were honest, took time to look at my car, reassure me it was ok, and did not charge me for the services because they stated they did not do anything to my car so they did not have to charge me.

I wish I had these guys in Chicago, because I would probably use them as my regular mechanic. Be at experience with a mechanic</review>

<rating>5</rating>< review>
These guys are absolutely amazing! I randomly lost acceleration and then could not get my 2002 Subaru Outback to start after pulling off to the side of the road while driving down the 5 freeway from Chico State area to Southern California.

While waiting 2 hours in the middle of nowhere with 1-2 bars and 3G, I pulled up CKM on a google search and explained my situation. Not wanting to spend a Friday night in Fresno, with full knowledge that a majority of shops would be closed for the weekend.

The shop was very patient with me on the phone and began working on my car almost instantly, explaining that I had a bad fuel pump. They quickly had NAPA expedite a new one and were unsure if they would have enough time to finish before closing.

I explained I did not want to be stranded in Fresno as it was not my intended destination nor did I look forward to being stranded for the entire weekend. To which the Craig Chin (the owner) told me he would drop me off at a nearby motel and come in on Saturday to work on my car himself if necessary.

We ended up getting the part we needed and after discussing what was being done to my car. Craig mentioned I should also change my fuel filter as a precaution and asked if I would like to do that as well or save $ on parts and labor and do it myself. He even gave me directions to the auto parts store!

After finally getting to my destination I looked up average repair costs for the same job in my area and was throughly impressed to discover that the work performed was a fair if not almost cheaper price when I could have be fully taken advantage of.

Thank You So Much Craig Chin and Family for your help.
+there's a dog to play with in the lobby (added bonus stress reliever)</review>

<Name>Martin O'Hara</Name><time>1549582561682<//time><Rate>1< /Rate>< Review>
If you've ever been at a mechanic to get your Nissan serviced and thought "man, this process is entirely too simple, straightforward, and stressfree!" - Nissan Serramonte Service might be just what you need!
Do you cherish the feeling of chasing after a group of toddlers who all put something in their mouth and run away giggling?
Do you not particularly need your car back right now?
Would you rather not know what is wrong with your car and instead receive vague suggestions and uncertain pricing?
How about communication -do you want to go 3 working days at a time without a response? Do you want to call to follow up on an unanswered question, only to find that an actual business with an actual phone in the year of two thousand and nineteen has a voicemail box that is full and cannot accept any more messages?
Is your idea of good service a choose your own adventure game where your choices are: a pleasant and helpful man who vanishes when you ask the slightest question or an aggressively condescending and pushy man who will actually call you but will push for you to make a decision without any information?
I realize I've done a terrible job proving just how worthy of your time Nissan Serramonte is. What if I told you your car could be under repair for 15 consecutive days in October, only for the same problem to arise in December? Hoooo boy what if I told you, what if you could take the car back to have someone take 7 days to look at it only to tell you it's an entirely different problem that conveniently just so happens to be the part that connects to the part previously replaced in October? What if it took 27 more days from that point to complete the service? What if, in the middle of being without your car for the second time in 3 months, a different division of the dealership could call you in the middle of dinner, asking if you wanted to sell your car and trade up to a new one, not knowing that your car was still being "worked" on?
I guess all I can say is if your money and time mean nothing to you, this is certainly a place that exists and you could, in theory, take your car to.

However, if you are a human being with reasonable expectations and a sense of dignity, avoid this place like the garbage fire it is.< /Review>

<user_id>114678765462480116177</user_id><user_name>Vic< /user_name>< Time>
1539055927015</Time>
<rate>1<//rate>< review>
Starts like this-

I hit a curb, and tweaked the front wheel. My fault, so I decide I'll pay for it directly.

I bring the Frontier to Nissan Serramonte. They say my steering rack needs replaced, and also the steering wheel "clockspring" needs to be replaced (that's what transmits the steering wheel cruise, radio, phone controls signals as the wheel is turned) So I pay around $2000 for them to do this work.

When I get the vehicle back, the stability control warning dashboard light is on, and my steering wheel is now really crooked. I mean, it's like this even as I drive away. Car goes really straight, (that part is better now) but only if you held the wheel at an obviously wrong angle. Really annoying to drive.

I knew it was wrong to drive away when things werent right, but it's a company car, and I needed my vehicle with the company logo on it, in order to park in the jobsite area.

So I have a series of text e changes with the service writer, explaining the problem, and he says bring it back any time, and they'll make it right. He never said there was any limit on the time to bring it back.

It was several months before I could make it back there. One reason is because each and every day I needed a vehicle with the company logo on it, I'm always working when the Svc Dept is open during the week, and another reason is that I always fly home on weekends, so I could never bring the vehicle back on Saturday when service is also open. So yes, it took quite a while to bring the vehicle back in. But it still had the stability control warning light on,  and the steering wheel was still crooked, just like when I picked it up. The passage of time had no bearing on these issues, because they were EXACTLY the same two issues as the day I drove it off the lot. Exactly the same issues I described to their previous service writer. Pretty obvious to any normal person that these are issues they left wrong when they first worked on it.

When I finally made it back in, the new service writer didnt care about the series of text exchanges I had with the previous service writer, ("Oh, he's gone, doesnt work here anymore") He didn't care that these items were the exact same problems as when they finished working on it before. He just says if I want it fixed, I gotta pay, and says these things could have happened in the interim between when I first took the vehicle and when I brought it back. Sure, it's my fault. Uh-huh, piss on my leg and tell me its raining. He says only the manager has the authority to waive the charges. Manager isnt in, but will be back later, etc..

So I pay hundreds of dollars to have them correct what they messed up the first time. I pay twice for their poor workmanship, and take my vehicle back again, only because I need it.

Then I call for the manager, who isn't in again, and leave a clear, concise message describing the issues, and asking for the charges to be waived, and repeated my cell number two times slowly.

The manager evidently didn't even care enough to call me back. Why should they? They already got my money, TWICE! Ok, hah hah, joke's on me. They win, I lose. That's what treatment I can expect from Nissan Serramonte.

Ok, Nissan Serramonte, I got your number.</review>

< Review>
This is a review that has been due for a very long time

After my accident in my old car, I was on the market for new one, I wasn't sure what brand I want at first, but then I finally decided to go with a NISSAN. I went to 6 different dealers before I bought my car. Every dealer has different prices, rules, attitudes, and whats worst they all say "oh we're the best" and they WONT stop calling. So I decided to give Alhambra Nissan a call and make a deal with them over the phone before I come in as I was already upset and done. The guy who picked up was very nice, I'm not sure if he still works in the company, but he really was the best. His sense of urgency was amazing, his customer service skills was great.  I started using Alhambra services to get oil and car wash. At 1st it was the worst ever. Every time I come there is new people, but it got better and better.
I moved to San Francisco about 2 years ago. As I was so disparate to find a dealer, and not just any dealer, a dealer who can really help me maintain my car and give me the service I need. I ended up going to (Nissan/Infiniti 1395 Van Ness Ave). As I was sitting in the waiting for my car, a lady named Jennifer came up to me and asked me if I doing ok or I would like a cup of coffee. I smiled and said I'm ok thank you. Then she ended up introducing herself as the manager and if I need anything please to let her know. The next time I visited Nissan I met a young guy named Neil, I don't know where to start about him, he is so nice and amazing, he knew exactly what's going on with my car and gave me an estimate time on when my car will be done. He was definitely the person to go too. Again the Manager Jennifer came out to check if everything was ok. Then after that Jennifer and Neil are my Nissan guys, I won't ever step a foot at the deal without them being there. I even call to make sure one of them are there.

Two weeks ago I went to the dealer as I needed oil change AGAIN, I came to find out Jennifer and Neil are no long in the company. I was so sad and literally devastated. I didn't want to deal with the new people, I was just upset and ready to leave. I didn't even want to start over and deal with the B.S.  Then I asked what happened, they didn't say anything and acted like they were busy on the computer, while clearly they weren't doing anything. I felt I was ignored as no one wants to help. What happened to the customer service? I don't understand!!  Then I asked someone who I met before Jennifer left, she told me Jennifer got transferred to this location (Serramonte Nissan 650 Serramonte Blvd). Then I made few phones calls and find out where she was, and when she starts. Today I went to 650 Serramnte and reconnected with Jennifer and got my car taken care off. It was really my best day ever. I always believe in great customer service, and that is why I followed Jennifer to her new job. I love her attention to details and also her active listening to my car needs. She introduced me the service manager, he was very nice, I felt I was part of the Nissan family. As of today 650 Serramonte Nissan will be my car new home THANK YOU THANK YOU THANK YOU.
And for who you reading this, make sure to ask for Jennifer and she will take care of you!!

Nicholas Ali Yassine!
P.S I'm extremely disappointed on how customer service changed at (1395 Van Ness ave Nissan) . I will never return that place.

P.P.S My friends on Yelp, give this dealer a shot You'll be impressed!<//Review>

<userid>118420681849258235160</userid><review>This review is for the Nissan Service Center.

Do not go there to service your vehicle. Go somewhere else. The schedule maint that they try to sell you are not even mention in the Nissan Service Manual.

During my last visit, I dropped off my car for regular oil and filter change service and the advisor sold me the "Nissan 30,000 mile scheduled maint service" priced around $600 and he told me the fluids in the car needed to be changed because they are past due for service and can cause damage.

Later I found out that the service that the sold me such as Cooling system D/F, Fuel System Maint, and Fuel Injector Maint aren't listed in the any Nissan manual.

I complaint to the service manager and asked for partial refund, through my credit card company but he refused, even thought he acknowledge that his advisors are crooks.
He told me that I will have to bring him to Court in order for me to get anything back.
I have complaint this incident to Nissan Consumer Compalint, BARS (Bureau of Auto Repair Services), BBB and will be filing small claim court against the dealer.

Crooks.. Crooks.. stay away from this service center....

Update***
A few months later, after filing with BARS , Service Center Manager finally agree to partial refund and send me a check for 380.00.

< review>
I am really neutral about this Nissan service location.

I went to get my 60k check up, and they offered a discount because he said, "Oh you just need an oil change" -- you'll have to pay $40 for that, and $20 cash for switching your tail light. I'VE never been asked to pay cash before, and it was really shady.

Granted that they finished the job, and got my tail light fixed.

However, when I hit my 70k, the service at SF Nissan asked if I had done my 60k check up, and told them what the guy at this place told me. I obviously was cheated out of a full service because they didn't change my air filter, check brakes, tire rotation etc. The guy at SF Nissan ended up doing a 60k check up for me making sure that my car was all up to date. I don't think I'll ever come by to this Serramonte Nissan.

Guys, be warned!< /review>
